INSERT INTO `knowledge_articlepage` VALUES (31,1,'Keeping Our Bees','Keeping Our Bees',NULL,'Celebrate World Bee Day 2019 with Except Biotechnologist Jon Woning','Celebrate World Bee Day 2019 with Except Biotechnologist Jon Woning',NULL,'2019-05-28','Today, following the recent UN report outlining the devastating degradation of our planets natural biodiversity, is World Bee Day. To celebrate these magnificent creatures which are vital for the preservation of earths ecological balance, we asked Jon Woning, Excepts resident biotechnologist and bee enthusiast, to talk us through the importance of cross-pollination in our society.','Today, following the recent UN report outlining the devastating degradation of our planets natural biodiversity, is World Bee Day. To celebrate these magnificent creatures which are vital for the preservation of earths ecological balance, we asked Jon Woning, Excepts resident biotechnologist and bee enthusiast, to talk us through the importance of cross-pollination in our society.','',NULL,1,1,'[{\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>\\u201cBees play a huge role in the systematic cultivation of fruit, as the main pollinators in orchards,\\u201d says Jon. \\u201cTogether with other pollination dependent crops, this represents a rough third of all our food on the planet.\\u201d While bees are the public image of cross-pollination, this critical natural process does not belong to the bees alone. A large number of insect species, including bumblebees, wasps, and flies, hold together our ecosystems with cross-pollination. These insects are a necessity for over 70% of wild species of plants, and a third of the world\\u2019s agricultural crops.</p>\"}, \"id\": \"6e892272-37a5-4dfa-8cbf-bd8440eda06e\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>The FAO estimates that between $235 and $577 billion (U.S.) worth of annual global food production relies on the direct contribution of pollinators, and over 4,000 different species of bees contribute to pollination. For a country like the UK, the value of the bees&#x27; services were estimated at \\u00a3200m a year. The retail value of what they pollinate was valued closer to \\u00a31bn (UK National Audit Office, 2007).</p>\"}, \"id\": \"bed9ca79-2324-405b-9842-4bb6ad0b7fc5\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>The honeybee is by far the most protected species, as they provide a source of economic value. The decline in honeybees signifies a terrifying trend for other insect species, that do not receive this protection. Insect populations in Europe have dwindled over 90% over the last two centuries, due to human interference.</p>\"}, \"id\": \"38c32f21-dc44-4a71-81de-49c9337f7cc8\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>\\u201cWorld Bee Day is a great opportunity to give these critical critters the attention they deserve,\\u201d says Jon. \\u201cBees are truly fascinating creatures, with complex societies and social structures that we as humans can aspire to. Their function as guardians of flora-rich ecosystems, ensures their place and purpose in this world.\\u201d</p>\"}, \"id\": \"6628899e-089b-4721-9214-fde3147178aa\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>There are around 20,000 species of bees, only one of which is the common honeybee. They come in many colours. Most bees don&#x27;t dance, and, only a few species make honey.</p>\"}, \"id\": \"1b3c96a9-8f71-4e83-bc4e-ba1b2f924f21\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>\\u201cWe have to recognise these insects\\u2019 pivotal role in the natural world. It\\u2019s critical to regard their well-being as a vital indicator for the health of our ecosystems. When our protected bees fall we will follow, given time.\\u201d</p>\"}, \"id\": \"30e865d2-0ebc-4f97-bce5-87f284b7b40b\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Important insect populations also suffer at the hands of our domestic efforts. Many gardens today are boarded up or turned into stone patches. Together with the huge grasslands which are used for agriculture \\u2013 but are deserts to bees \\u2013 our own backyards make up part of these shrinking ecosystems. As a result, the bees\\u2019 natural territory, and their ability to spread from ecosystem to ecosystem has been severely limited.</p>\"}, \"id\": \"2d02a719-2512-4499-bbe3-73cb18fc7f06\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>\\u201cBecause of this fact, a lot of flowering flora, including those in your gardens, have seen a decline. Without bees and other pollinators, the world is literally a less colourful place. Individuals have the ability to make a large positive impact on the decline of bee species and the ecosystems that support them. Please help the bees around you, and replace some of the stone and grass with some (native) flowers!\\u201d</p>\"}, \"id\": \"89360b4d-2cb8-4be6-b35b-e465cb6ecb9b\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>If you want to find out more on World Bee Day, Jon recommends the following further reading and watching materials:</p>\"}, \"id\": \"858e0036-da10-41e4-b24d-184dc99fde37\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<ul><li>More Than Honey (2012) is a film on the different beekeeping practices in the world, and the status of their existence.<br/></li><li>For the Dutch among us who enjoy a well illustrated piece of educational reading, check out Het Complete Bijenboek (ISBN 978 94 6143 159 2).<br/></li><li>If you want to find out more about why we need bees, read this report by the NRDC on how Nature\\u2019s Tiny Workers Put Food on Our Tables.<br/></li><li>Or check in with your local beekeeper society. These organisation often provide courses or other material on the subject of bees, as well being an excellent source of fresh locally sourced honey (definitely worth a try).<br/></li></ul>\"}, \"id\": \"77ecc3bb-2ca9-4a03-86dc-6a55905c9595\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Jon Woning is a biotechnologist by choice, and curious by nature. He has earned his beekeeping certificate, and has recently adopted his first hive.</p>\"}, \"id\": \"bacbeeef-4b99-4fc6-a70e-e55d3b54ba70\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}]','[{\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>\\u201cBees play a huge role in the systematic cultivation of fruit, as the main pollinators in orchards,\\u201d says Jon. \\u201cTogether with other pollination dependent crops, this represents a rough third of all our food on the planet.\\u201d While bees are the public image of cross-pollination, this critical natural process does not belong to the bees alone. A large number of insect species, including bumblebees, wasps, and flies, hold together our ecosystems with cross-pollination. These insects are a necessity for over 70% of wild species of plants, and a third of the world\\u2019s agricultural crops.</p>\"}, \"id\": \"6e892272-37a5-4dfa-8cbf-bd8440eda06e\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>The FAO estimates that between $235 and $577 billion (U.S.) worth of annual global food production relies on the direct contribution of pollinators, and over 4,000 different species of bees contribute to pollination. For a country like the UK, the value of the bees&#x27; services were estimated at \\u00a3200m a year. The retail value of what they pollinate was valued closer to \\u00a31bn (UK National Audit Office, 2007).</p>\"}, \"id\": \"bed9ca79-2324-405b-9842-4bb6ad0b7fc5\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>The honeybee is by far the most protected species, as they provide a source of economic value. The decline in honeybees signifies a terrifying trend for other insect species, that do not receive this protection. Insect populations in Europe have dwindled over 90% over the last two centuries, due to human interference.</p>\"}, \"id\": \"38c32f21-dc44-4a71-81de-49c9337f7cc8\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>\\u201cWorld Bee Day is a great opportunity to give these critical critters the attention they deserve,\\u201d says Jon. \\u201cBees are truly fascinating creatures, with complex societies and social structures that we as humans can aspire to. Their function as guardians of flora-rich ecosystems, ensures their place and purpose in this world.\\u201d</p>\"}, \"id\": \"6628899e-089b-4721-9214-fde3147178aa\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>There are around 20,000 species of bees, only one of which is the common honeybee. They come in many colours. Most bees don&#x27;t dance, and, only a few species make honey.</p>\"}, \"id\": \"1b3c96a9-8f71-4e83-bc4e-ba1b2f924f21\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>\\u201cWe have to recognise these insects\\u2019 pivotal role in the natural world. It\\u2019s critical to regard their well-being as a vital indicator for the health of our ecosystems. When our protected bees fall we will follow, given time.\\u201d</p>\"}, \"id\": \"30e865d2-0ebc-4f97-bce5-87f284b7b40b\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Important insect populations also suffer at the hands of our domestic efforts. Many gardens today are boarded up or turned into stone patches. Together with the huge grasslands which are used for agriculture \\u2013 but are deserts to bees \\u2013 our own backyards make up part of these shrinking ecosystems. As a result, the bees\\u2019 natural territory, and their ability to spread from ecosystem to ecosystem has been severely limited.</p>\"}, \"id\": \"2d02a719-2512-4499-bbe3-73cb18fc7f06\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>\\u201cBecause of this fact, a lot of flowering flora, including those in your gardens, have seen a decline. Without bees and other pollinators, the world is literally a less colourful place. Individuals have the ability to make a large positive impact on the decline of bee species and the ecosystems that support them. Please help the bees around you, and replace some of the stone and grass with some (native) flowers!\\u201d</p>\"}, \"id\": \"89360b4d-2cb8-4be6-b35b-e465cb6ecb9b\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>If you want to find out more on World Bee Day, Jon recommends the following further reading and watching materials:</p>\"}, \"id\": \"858e0036-da10-41e4-b24d-184dc99fde37\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<ul><li>More Than Honey (2012) is a film on the different beekeeping practices in the world, and the status of their existence.<br/></li><li>For the Dutch among us who enjoy a well illustrated piece of educational reading, check out Het Complete Bijenboek (ISBN 978 94 6143 159 2).<br/></li><li>If you want to find out more about why we need bees, read this report by the NRDC on how Nature\\u2019s Tiny Workers Put Food on Our Tables.<br/></li><li>Or check in with your local beekeeper society. These organisation often provide courses or other material on the subject of bees, as well being an excellent source of fresh locally sourced honey (definitely worth a try).<br/></li></ul>\"}, \"id\": \"77ecc3bb-2ca9-4a03-86dc-6a55905c9595\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Jon Woning is a biotechnologist by choice, and curious by nature. He has earned his beekeeping certificate, and has recently adopted his first hive.</p>\"}, \"id\": \"bacbeeef-4b99-4fc6-a70e-e55d3b54ba70\", \"type\": \"paragraph_block\"}]','[]',NULL,25,NULL),(32,1,'Natural Capital & new innovation strategies','Natural Capital & new innovation strategies',NULL,'How to accelerate natural value systems','How to accelerate natural value systems',NULL,'2019-09-17','The land we grow our food on, water that flows through it, animals and plants living in this environment, and the oceans - the birthplace of life. This, and more, is our natural capital; the value represented by our ecosystems, species, and everything in between that we rely on to persist on this planet. All of our natural systems are declining fast, and this threatens our future. It puts at risk the continuation of any business with a complex supply chain, and jeopardizes the resource availability of any nation.\r\n\r\nThe Natural Capital (NC) movement attempts to halt and reverse this trend by embedding the value of natural systems into economic systems. This article talks about how Natural Capital works, what the pitfalls and opportunities of such a system are, and how we can accelerate implementation in government and business.','The land we grow our food on, water that flows through it, animals and plants living in this environment, and the oceans - the birthplace of life. This, and more, is our natural capital; the value represented by our ecosystems, species, and everything in between that we rely on to persist on this planet. All of our natural systems are declining fast, and this threatens our future. It puts at risk the continuation of any business with a complex supply chain, and jeopardizes the resource availability of any nation.\r\n\r\nThe Natural Capital (NC) movement attempts to halt and reverse this trend by embedding the value of natural systems into economic systems. This article talks about how Natural Capital works, what the pitfalls and opportunities of such a system are, and how we can accelerate implementation in government and business.','',NULL,1,1,'[{\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>While there is debate about NC as a concept, it is one of the few answers we have. Organizations around the world are moving to implement it because of rapidly increasing ecological destruction. But there is much to be done, and progress is slow. There are opportunities to accelerate and improve Natural Capital based on innovative systems solutions for business and policy alike. Solutions that not only conserve nature but puts the front runners of NC in a position of significant advantage, both in business and policy.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"44844abd-304f-443a-b0a0-9a5a8c03099b\"}, {\"value\": {\"size\": \"h3\", \"heading_text\": \"Why Natural Capital?\"}, \"type\": \"heading_block\", \"id\": \"42d49fe1-6274-4ce4-934c-a21216a18cb4\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>The concept of Natural Capital has been around for more than a century and is not without controversy. Debate about its ethical foundations has been going on for decades, raising ethical questions without clear answers, but the global decline of nature pressures us for action. Nature currently has limited economic value, causing it to be regularly sacrificed. This &#x27;<a href=\\\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tragedy_of_the_commons\\\">tragedy of the commons</a>&#x27; plagues conservation efforts and the debate has delayed solutions resulting in preventable losses.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"8b0622e9-b348-4307-b347-f742acd03f52\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>At the <a href=\\\"http://www.naturalcapitalforum.com/\\\">2013 World Forum on Natural Capital</a> in Edinburgh, organized by the Scottish Wildlife Trust, most policy and business representatives agreed it\\u2019s time to take action, putting the ethical discussion to the background. Barry Gardiner, UK shadow minister for the environment, said it most poignantly:</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"6445f2db-65fa-422c-8cab-6f971157663f\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"We use nature because it gives us value, and we destroy it because it\'s free. Nature should be given the rightful value it deserves, it\\u2019s the only real way we can safeguard our natural resources for the future.\", \"attribute_name\": \"\"}, \"type\": \"block_quote\", \"id\": \"25bf9a23-4462-4b29-b801-826714dc752d\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Because NC is one of the few tools that allows direct action to be taken, the message is to implement it as fast as we can. How can we do this? The challenge can be summarized as follows; what mechanisms can we use to make natural capital work, how to value nature in all its facets, and how to create an advantage for policy and business for rapid implementation.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"fb383a1c-da95-4a41-bc8a-34b1dcf28072\"}, {\"value\": {\"size\": \"h3\", \"heading_text\": \"What mechanisms make Natural Capital work?\"}, \"type\": \"heading_block\", \"id\": \"03beb8bc-624e-483e-948b-618ab82f2548\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>The solution supported by the largest NGO&#x27;s introduces national NC profit and loss balance sheets in each country and company, and tracks this balance as is done with finance. These balance sheets express Natural Capital both in terms of quantity and quality of resources (amounts of forests, water, biodiversity, etc), and, where possible, as currency. For every asset that disappears from the balance sheet, something else needs to be brought back. This functions to increase awareness and transparency about the state of our natural resources, and improves their management. When successful, Natural Capital Accounting (NCA) injects a balancing system for our planet\\u2019s physical limits to growth into an economy currently aimed at capitalizing on limitless growth.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"f33f290d-04e2-437c-9335-69640548cf9c\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Implementing Natural Capital is not without risk, as demonstrated by the carbon credit scheme that often creates perverse incentives, shifting damage from one place to another due to incomplete valuation. To prevent this, NCA needs to take into account the full spectrum of value we recognise today, and leave room for values that appear in the future. Values that cannot be expressed in a monetary equivalent need to appear on the balance sheets in their qualitative form. It will not be possible to account for all value, but this should not hold us back. As Professor Dieter Helm explained at the forum in Edinburgh:</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"d7d5232c-44e1-4e4e-b6c8-4de45911e028\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"We do not need to be entirely correct in our assessment of Natural Capital. Even if we\'re only 80% or even 50% in the ballpark, that\\u2019s at least better than the value of zero we have currently. We need to act, now, to prevent further losses to an already marginalized system, regardless of not being able to accurately value Natural Capital.\", \"attribute_name\": \"\"}, \"type\": \"block_quote\", \"id\": \"80319f74-f791-4f63-8f44-60c6b4a9dd4f\"}, {\"value\": {\"caption\": \"\", \"attribution\": \"\", \"image\": 24}, \"type\": \"image_block\", \"id\": \"37660d11-4b32-4f6b-833b-32d0112f3fdd\"}, {\"value\": {\"size\": \"h3\", \"heading_text\": \"How do we value nature?\"}, \"type\": \"heading_block\", \"id\": \"0f230716-89e4-4588-96e4-683f31f73e47\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>This is undoubtedly the greatest challenge of Natural Capital as a concept. What value does a tree have? Ask a hundred scientists and economists and you will get a hundred different answers. In order for NC to work, we need to agree on a basis of valuation.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"7d39d443-f8f6-48c8-8bfb-ecd3b149fba9\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>A tree is worth more than just the price of its wood, as it provides a home to many animals, it acts as shade in summer, it buffers and filters rainwater, it cleans the air, and it also supplies a number of other ecosystem services. It may also be valuable in other terms, for example culturally, and for its role in the ecosystem as a whole. Therefore, the value of a tree in its entirety isn\\u2019t the same as the price for its wood in the store, and can be expressed in a different manner, for example in liters of water buffered and filtered, its contribution to biodiversity and well being, and so on.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"c4e1f866-2b30-41c9-99e5-ceec887ab075\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Quite a few studies have attempted to account for some of these values and converted them into currency. Research conducted by <a href=\\\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19755530\\\">Johnson and Wardle</a> gave the Canadian Boreal forest a value of US$ 3.7 trillion for all of its ecosystem services and carbon sequestration. Another study from 1997 by <a href=\\\"http://www.uvm.edu/giee/publications/Nature_Paper.pdf\\\">Costanza et. al</a> put a pricetag of US$ 33 trillion on the world\\u2019s biosphere\\u2019s ecosystem services. These and other studies give starting points for value estimation, while there are certainly large gaps to cover. To find and fill these gaps, a more inclusive framework to assess value is necessary.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"3196c1d5-81c9-43a9-a69c-5c52ba55a68f\"}, {\"value\": {\"size\": \"h3\", \"heading_text\": \"SiD as a structure for value\"}, \"type\": \"heading_block\", \"id\": \"4daf9370-e2af-4d85-81cc-af7399bd2023\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>The <a href=\\\"http://except.nl/en/articles/148-symbiosis-in-development-sid\\\">Symbiosis in Development (SiD)</a> systems analysis framework is such a tool. It can be used to assess the full spectrum of value for any given subject, including the relational values of the system as a whole. Its flexible structure allows room for future discovery while providing clarity to start valuing with limited insight today.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"49929fcc-4759-4707-88d3-fbbfe78d41a2\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Using SiD the value of the tree can be seen on three &#x27;scales&#x27;: the object (direct physical) value, the value of its network (services and relations), and its systemic value as a whole. The first being the easiest to assess, and the last the hardest but having the most impact. Combining these three scales results in a estimation of the tree\\u2019s Natural Capital value.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"5948f13c-d421-4462-88df-393f1a9a4704\"}, {\"value\": {\"caption\": \"This diagram is a simplified example of the structure of SiD\\u2019s value assessment when applied to a tree.\", \"attribution\": \"\", \"image\": 25}, \"type\": \"image_block\", \"id\": \"4edcea54-2eea-4e68-ac8d-14ae528bc5f6\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Using SiD, there are opportunities for other values to join the party, such as transparency, diversity, health, and wellbeing. SiD reserves room for these values, allowing them to be slotted in once research makes them available. Because it is a universal framework, it works for other measurements as well, allowing it to be inclusive of other movements such as social justice or poverty alleviation and stand stronger together. This flexibility prevents the system becoming solidified once adopted, preventing perverse incentives that occur when real value and value in the system are dissonant (an issue that plagues carbon trading). Tracking the flexibility of the Natural Capital system is therefore essential.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"607c9f04-4c81-41e1-a83c-52a4891eda08\"}, {\"value\": {\"size\": \"h3\", \"heading_text\": \"Giving Natural Capital teeth\"}, \"type\": \"heading_block\", \"id\": \"846aaf8a-c7dc-40e7-b5cb-a40fccd5c298\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>There are frameworks for valuation, which can be filled in using existing research. Then incentives are needed for organizations to implement them. Using systemic innovation strategies, the most effective approaches can be explored. As a trial, a small interdisciplinary team at Except, a sustainability strategy firm, held a short systems exploration session and came up with a few approaches. It was discovered that effective solutions are those that make Natural Capital a base economic requirement for growth, rooting it into the core of the economy.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"2638841e-e68a-416f-90a0-5672ec143e45\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>One approach is to create a secondary currency backed by Natural Capital rather than gold. This means Natural Capital is not expressed in Dollars, Euros or Yen, but in its own currency, for example called the GreenBack. This currency is purely digital, relying on similar technology as BitCoin, and coupled to the balance sheets of nations, capturing both qualitative and quantitative values in separate indicators. When demand for this GreenBack goes up, a direct increase in demand for Natural Capital results. This creates a natural marketplace where the only way to grow wealth is to grow Natural Capital. This currency thus couples economic growth to its necessary precursor: the resources our planet needs to sustain economic growth.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"0d7672b6-a04a-4941-b9c3-b015c0a37b5b\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Solutions like these accelerate the implementation of Natural Capital, but both business and government have their own challenges. What are the opportunities for countries and companies to implement NC?</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"99aa3be5-b09a-499a-be5d-e435a5d3765d\"}, {\"value\": {\"caption\": \"\", \"attribution\": \"\", \"image\": 26}, \"type\": \"image_block\", \"id\": \"8db23d3e-2c4f-4b55-921c-d09f0279d6f5\"}, {\"value\": {\"size\": \"h3\", \"heading_text\": \"Opportunities to accelerate NCA in policy\"}, \"type\": \"heading_block\", \"id\": \"357fcd21-8c87-473e-b88d-cbb815a04bdb\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"In 50 years\\u2019 time we will look back and say that our governments were economically illiterate. They simply did not understand the true value of the most important service providers on our planet. We will marvel that they failed to capture and make explicit the value of Natural Capital and ecosystem services in their national accounts.\", \"attribute_name\": \"Barry Gardiner, MP\"}, \"type\": \"block_quote\", \"id\": \"522a3a0c-b111-4de8-bfcb-908cbac23600\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Several projects researching the role of NC in policy are underway, for example TEEB, a global research project through the European Union. But progress is slow, hampered by lack of oversight, tools for valuation, accessible knowledge databases, and stakeholder awareness. These challenges can be more effectively solved with innovative systems-thinking than traditional approaches, saving resources and time. And time is of the essence here. One way to speed up the process is to apply distributed innovation mechanisms, such as crowd-solutioning and serious gaming. These approaches have managed to resolve in weeks highly complex problems such as <a href=\\\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/sarikabansal/2011/09/28/crowdsourcing-gamers-solve-protein/\\\">unraveling the secrets of protein folding</a>, which previously took teams of scientists many years. If strategies such as these were to be applied to the issues that hold back Natural Capital, solutions could be implemented at a much faster rate, and Natural Capital Accounting could be in place in many countries within the next decade.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"db76a7be-8278-4031-891e-ee4205d576da\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>But, Natural Capital can only be effective if it&#x27;s adopted voluntarily by both government and business. Enforcement takes too long and the stick causes loopholes, while the carrot accelerates the process. Why would a profit driven company be interested to implement and invest in Natural Capital?</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"df6328ea-9e72-4f61-a80c-ed285ee7ebea\"}, {\"value\": {\"caption\": \"\", \"attribution\": \"\", \"image\": 27}, \"type\": \"image_block\", \"id\": \"c0cc39ac-a508-4a53-85e4-fce207d37b4d\"}, {\"value\": {\"size\": \"h3\", \"heading_text\": \"Advantages of embedding NCA in business\"}, \"type\": \"heading_block\", \"id\": \"220236c4-6cef-408a-91bb-03c72738d037\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>At first sight, business may not seem to have an interest in Natural Capital or Natural Capital Accounting, as it does not directly lead to profit. But there are several reasons why this is not only advantageous, but critical to the survival of business today and tomorrow.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"293c87b5-bf70-442b-a1ab-1c92c3171b6b\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>In complex supply chains, change comes quickly and strikes hard. Most companies rely on one or more natural resources somewhere in their supply chain, yet may not be aware of where and how. Tracking NC is essential to ensure continued business in the short and long term. If a sizeable business is not tracking this, it is not conducting proper risk management.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"e24cd87c-5d9b-423e-8e7a-d4509f48b5f0\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>In addition, business can use NC to find valuable ecosystems services while improving CSR performance at the same time. For example, companies have found bio-based alternatives to artificial or fossil resources that save money and provide long term sourcing security.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"06dc9eab-847a-49c4-90b7-2df3eaf3af6d\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>It is also good for businesses to be ahead of the curve when it comes to issues that governments will eventually demand. Waiting to be forced into something through regulation risks costly solutions being enforced. Also, being one of the first to start NC accounting has its perks. It allows an organization to shape the conversation, be more opportunistic with investments, and get public recognition for leading the good fight. This has been shown by Puma, which started publishing the first Environmental Profit &amp; Loss Account (EPLA) under direction of their holding company Kering, and already tracked 145 million in environmental impacts in <a href=\\\"http://about.puma.com/wp-content/themes/aboutPUMA_theme/financial-report/pdf/EPL080212final.pdf\\\">2010</a>. This resulted in positive press globally, several companies following suit, and creating a catch-up game for everyone else.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"310f8b67-938a-4e49-af63-27b8199340e7\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Lastly, insurance companies are becoming interested in Natural Capital Accounting. After all, threats to resources that a company relies on are threats to the company, and insurance will go up or become unavailable. And it is not just insurance firms. Standards &amp; Poor\\u2019s, one of the Big-Three credit rating firms, is investigating Natural Capital Accounting as a new input for the same reasons, directly affecting a company\\u2019s credit rating. That should be reason enough for the big players out there to start moving.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"a57c8c76-ad5b-4bba-a76e-b035900396e7\"}, {\"value\": {\"size\": \"h4\", \"heading_text\": \"Making it happen\"}, \"type\": \"heading_block\", \"id\": \"e3db8b60-8a68-4e70-81ca-d919666bc819\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>There are many reasons to start implementing NC as fast as possible. A structured and systemic approach is critical to make it succeed. This is why solutions like SiD exist. We call on the front runners of NC to aim higher and gain the advantage of using innovative systems tools and implementation strategies, such as natural currencies, crowd-solutioning and systemic risk assessment. The front runners in policy, business, and NGOs should be brought together to collectively accelerate the process and support each other. It is in our joint interest to do so. We have the tools, expertise, and manpower to do this, so let\\u2019s make Natural Capital accounting a reality within a few years, and gain huge benefits for each organization and society alike.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"b0a5e7ce-8c2c-4788-9303-191c3e01f344\"}]','[{\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>While there is debate about NC as a concept, it is one of the few answers we have. Organizations around the world are moving to implement it because of rapidly increasing ecological destruction. But there is much to be done, and progress is slow. There are opportunities to accelerate and improve Natural Capital based on innovative systems solutions for business and policy alike. Solutions that not only conserve nature but puts the front runners of NC in a position of significant advantage, both in business and policy.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"44844abd-304f-443a-b0a0-9a5a8c03099b\"}, {\"value\": {\"size\": \"h3\", \"heading_text\": \"Why Natural Capital?\"}, \"type\": \"heading_block\", \"id\": \"42d49fe1-6274-4ce4-934c-a21216a18cb4\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>The concept of Natural Capital has been around for more than a century and is not without controversy. Debate about its ethical foundations has been going on for decades, raising ethical questions without clear answers, but the global decline of nature pressures us for action. Nature currently has limited economic value, causing it to be regularly sacrificed. This &#x27;<a href=\\\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tragedy_of_the_commons\\\">tragedy of the commons</a>&#x27; plagues conservation efforts and the debate has delayed solutions resulting in preventable losses.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"8b0622e9-b348-4307-b347-f742acd03f52\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>At the <a href=\\\"http://www.naturalcapitalforum.com/\\\">2013 World Forum on Natural Capital</a> in Edinburgh, organized by the Scottish Wildlife Trust, most policy and business representatives agreed it\\u2019s time to take action, putting the ethical discussion to the background. Barry Gardiner, UK shadow minister for the environment, said it most poignantly:</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"6445f2db-65fa-422c-8cab-6f971157663f\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"We use nature because it gives us value, and we destroy it because it\'s free. Nature should be given the rightful value it deserves, it\\u2019s the only real way we can safeguard our natural resources for the future.\", \"attribute_name\": \"\"}, \"type\": \"block_quote\", \"id\": \"25bf9a23-4462-4b29-b801-826714dc752d\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Because NC is one of the few tools that allows direct action to be taken, the message is to implement it as fast as we can. How can we do this? The challenge can be summarized as follows; what mechanisms can we use to make natural capital work, how to value nature in all its facets, and how to create an advantage for policy and business for rapid implementation.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"fb383a1c-da95-4a41-bc8a-34b1dcf28072\"}, {\"value\": {\"size\": \"h3\", \"heading_text\": \"What mechanisms make Natural Capital work?\"}, \"type\": \"heading_block\", \"id\": \"03beb8bc-624e-483e-948b-618ab82f2548\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>The solution supported by the largest NGO&#x27;s introduces national NC profit and loss balance sheets in each country and company, and tracks this balance as is done with finance. These balance sheets express Natural Capital both in terms of quantity and quality of resources (amounts of forests, water, biodiversity, etc), and, where possible, as currency. For every asset that disappears from the balance sheet, something else needs to be brought back. This functions to increase awareness and transparency about the state of our natural resources, and improves their management. When successful, Natural Capital Accounting (NCA) injects a balancing system for our planet\\u2019s physical limits to growth into an economy currently aimed at capitalizing on limitless growth.</p>\"}, \"type\": \"paragraph_block\", \"id\": \"f33f290d-04e2-437c-9335-69640548cf9c\"}, {\"value\": {\"text\": \"<p>Implementing Natural Capital is not without risk, as demonstrated by the carbon credit scheme that often creates perverse incentives, shifting damage from one place to another due to incomplete valuation. To prevent t